
[1]colonnade

   COLONNADE, n.

   1. In architecture, a peristyle of a circular figure, or a series of
   columns, disposed in a circle, and insulated within side.

   2. Any series of range of columns.

   A polystyle colonnade is a range of columns too great to be taken in by
   the eye at a single view; as that of the palace of St. Peter at Rome,
   consisting of 284 columns of the Doric order.
